huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: This hunt unit encompasses low elevation desert and higher mountainous sagebrush terrain, with the pronghorn distributed throughout the unit.  Road access is good throughout the unit, with one area-Bare Top-closed to motorized vehicles.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS:
Cellular phone coverage is spotty on this hunt unit. Satellite phones do work in the area. A "Spot Tracker" type of satellite messaging device for safety can be used if you decide to camp in an area without cell phone service and do not wish to drive to reach service. Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.

Camps should be kept clean to prevent bear incidents. Food should be kept inside vehicles or bear-proof containers. Coolers are not bear-proof. Bears have gotten into camps in the past. Number and severity of bear incidents differ by year depending on weather and other food availability. Meat and garbage should be put away inside a vehicle or hung in a tree above 8 feet off the ground and 3 feet away from the trunk or any branches of the tree.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically between the hunting seasons.  Be prepared for rain, lightning, snow, wind and heat.  It is quite common on clear mornings for clouds to build through the morning and have thunderstorms in the afternoon.  Be very cautious of lightning while hunting on high ridges or exposed slopes.  Early fall snow storms occur occasionally in this area.  Most years the snow will melt off within a day or two until through the first week of October.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Scouting Tips:
Pronghorn are fairly habitual and can be found in the same general area from late summer through the hunt. Pronghorn are best scouted from a distance using a spotting scope or binoculars so they donâ€™t leave the area. They are most active in the morning and evening when the temperatures are cooler; these are the best times to scout.

Behavior:
Like other wildlife, they are most active in the early mornings and evenings, but they can be up and moving any time of the day. Most of the time they are in desert scrub/sagebrush flat areas. If the weather is extremely hot, they will often seek shade during the middle part of the day. Pronghorn are herd animals. You will often see groups of does and fawns with only a few bucks mixed in during the fall. During the rut, bucks will separate from other males to find does to mate with. The rest of the year, the bucks are usually with other pronghorn.

Buck vs Doe:
Hunters can tell bucks from does by several characteristics. Bucks will have larger horns and a black cheek patch.

Pronghorn rut:
The pronghorn rut usually starts the end of September.

Where to find pronghorn:
Pronghorn are scattered throughout the appropriate habitat on this unit. They can be found in agricultural fields and in desert scrub or mountainous sage brush areas. They typically stay out of heavily treed and cliffy areas.

Recommended areas in the West Daggett:
Good areas to hunt include Lucerne Valley, Death Valley, Phil Pico, Conner Basin, and private property (if you have written permission).

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: 90% Public Land - US Forest Service lands and BLM.  There is some private property in this unit.  Please obtain written permission before hunting private property.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:

Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.

huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The boundary of this hunt unit does not include Tribal Trust Lands.  There is private land included in the hunt, however, the majority of the sheep can be found on public land.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Daggett and Summit counties-Boundary begins at the Burnt Fork drainage bottom and the Utah-Wyoming state line; east along this state line to the Flaming Gorge Reservoir main channel western shoreline(on the east side of Lucerne Point); west around Lucerne Point to the Utah-Wyoming state line (includes Lucerne Point); west along the state line to the western shore of Flaming Gorge Reservoir; southeast along this shoreline to Cart Creek; south along this creek to US-191; south on US-191 to the Uintah-Daggett County line (summit of the Uinta Mountains); west on this county line to the head of Burnt Fork drainage bottom(Divide Pass/Island Lake); north along this drainage bottom to the Utah-Wyoming state line. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Dutch John, Kings Peak. Boundary questions? Call Vernal office, 435-781-9453.
